[1] South Korea, XX new cases - MOH 13 Jun 2015
Date: Sat 13 Jun 2015
Source: South Korean Ministry of Health [in Korean, trans. by Korean subscribers, edited]
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323376


12 additional MERS cases, a total of 138
----------------------------------------------
The Ministry of Health and Welfare's MERS-CoV Task Force as of 13 Jun, has confirmed 12 additional positive cases of MERS-CoV (12 Jun 2015).

- 4 diagnosed cases have been in contact with case no. 16, 3 of them are suspected to be infected at the Dae Cheong Hospital (22-28 May 2015), and 1 case at the Gunyang University Hospital (28 - 30 May 2015).

- 2 diagnosed cases have been in contact with case no. 14, suspected place of infection is Samsung Medical Center Emergency Room (27 - 28 May 2015).

- 1 of the diagnosed cases is an ambulance driver, who was in contact while transporting case no. 76 on [5-6 Jun 2015].

- Remaining 5 cases are related cases at Samsung Medical Center and are currently under epidemiological investigation.

- Meanwhile, the Task Force has announced one fatality case; it is the 14th death due to MERS-CoV.

- The 14th fatality, case no. 118 (female, 67 year old, hypothyroidism/hypertension) had been in contact with case no. 14 at the Pyeongtaek Good Morning Hospital from 25-27 May 2015], and has been quarantined from 9 Jun 2015 at the Ajou University Hospital. She was diagnosed on 10 Jun 2015 during hospitalization, but her state deteriorated and she died 13 Jun 2015 (at 3:30 AM).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As of this latest report, the total number of laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection is now 138 cases including 14 deaths bringing the reported case fatality rate to 10.1 percent. As mentioned below, unfortunately the majority of the cases were in the hospital for other medical reasons, hence they are at serious risk of severe morbidity and higher risk of mortality.

Noteworthy in the descriptions of the cases: one of the cases is a 4th generation case, an ambulance driver who transported a 3rd generation case to the hospital. A key concern at present is the volume of 4th generation cases -- those cases whose exposure was after significant control measures were implemented.

A list of hospitals that have had MERS-CoV infected individuals come to the hospital can be found at the MOH website as a downloadable pdf file: http://english.mw.go.kr/front_eng/al/sal0201vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=1002&MENU_ID=100203&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323365

A map showing the locations of the confirmed cases can be found at http://news.kbs.co.kr/news/NewsView.do?SEARCH_NEWS_CODE=3087507 (the webpage is in Korean).

The HealthMap/ProMED map of South Korea can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3433313,195 and a map of South Korea showing provinces can be found at http://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm. A link to an information webpage showing locations of MERS screening clinics, an epidemic curve and other data from the task force can be found at http://issue.visualdive.co.kr/mers/. - Mod.MPP]

